Line breaking rules in East Asian languages
The line breaking rules in East Asian languages specify how to wrap East Asian Language text such as Chinese, Japanese, and Korean. Certain characters in those languages should not come at the end of a line, certain characters should not come at the start of a line, and some characters should never be split up across two lines. func playSE(name string, volume int) error { p, ok := ses[name] if ok { p.Rewind() p.Play() } else { bs, err := audiosrc.SEFiles.ReadFile(fmt.Sprintf("se/%s.ogg", name)) if err != nil { return err } seD, err := vorbis.DecodeWithSampleRate(context.SampleRate(), bytes.NewReader(bs)) if err != nil { return err } p, err := context.NewPlayer(seD) if err != nil { return err } ses[name] = p // We assume the volume of the same SE is not changed, // and set its volume statically. p.SetVolume(float64(volume) / 100) p.Play() } return nil }
